  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a felony in most jurisdictions, including the United States. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (dirty money) appear legal (clean money). This is typically done by disguising the origins of the money through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions.\n\nIn the United States, money laundering is prosecuted under federal law, primarily through the Money Laundering Control Act of 1986 (Title 18, U.S. Code, Sections 1956 and 1957). Violations can result in severe penalties, including substantial fines and lengthy prison sentences. For example, under U.S. federal law, individuals convicted of money laundering can face up to 20 years in prison for each offense, and fines can reach up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction, whichever is greater.\n\nAdditionally, many states have their own laws criminalizing money laundering, and penalties can vary depending on the specific circumstances of the case, such as the amount of money involved and the defendant's role in the scheme.\n\nInternational laws and treaties also address money laundering. For instance, the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) sets international standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing, and member countries are expected to implement these standards into their domestic laws.",
